{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds (P95, P90, P50, P10, P5) for every component-KPI group using the full metric.csv series. The aggregated table metric_kpi_thresholds is stored in the kernel and shows many OS and application KPIs across components (IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02, Tomcat*, Mysql*, Redis*, apache02, etc.). Next, per the diagnosis workflow, we should perform anomaly detection on the incident time window (March 7, 2021 11:00–11:30 CST, i.e., timestamps between 1615086000 and 1615087800). We must use the precomputed global thresholds (do not recompute after filtering). The immediate goal is to find which component-KPIs have values exceeding their global P95 within the incident window and to summarize these anomalies compactly (counts, earliest occurrence, max severity) to prioritize candidates for deeper trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the existing metric_kpi_thresholds in kernel, filter metric.csv to the incident window timestamps >=1615086000 and <=1615087800. Join each metric row with its corresponding group's p95 from metric_kpi_thresholds. Mark a row as an anomaly if value > p95. Aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id and kpi_name to produce: anomaly_count (number of anomalous points in window), earliest_anomaly_ts (minimum timestamp of anomaly), max_value (maximum value observed in window), and p95 (group threshold). Store the full anomaly rows table in kernel variable metric_anomalies. Return a compact summary table (at most 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value, p95. If no anomalies are found using p95, indicate that explicitly in the returned output." 
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output (anomalies_summary), we have a compact list of component-KPI groups that exceeded their global P95 within the incident window. Notable items: Redis02 OSLinux_FILESYSTEM_INodeUsedPercent had 5 anomalous points (earliest 11:02), Tomcat02 MEMORY_NoCacheMemPerc had 4 anomalies (earliest 11:01), several ServiceTest* app.cnt/app.mrt anomalies cluster at 11:29, apache01 shows multiple CPU-related anomalies around 11:00–11:26, MG01 shows JVM thread/runtime anomalies, and Redis02 shows unusually high redis CPU metrics at 11:28. These give two temporal clusters: early anomalies near 11:00–11:05 (Tomcat02, Redis02 FS inode, apache01, MG01) and late anomalies near 11:28–11:29 (ServiceTest* app.mrt/app.cnt, Redis02 redis CPU, IG01 JVM runtime). Per the workflow, the next step is fault identification: find consecutive anomaly runs (fault segments) for the top anomalous component-KPI groups and quantify their duration and severity. This will let us filter isolated spikes and prioritize candidate faults for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the existing metric_anomalies (or recompute by joining metric.csv filtered to timestamps 1615086000–1615087800 with metric_kpi_thresholds.p95), select the top 10 anomalous component-KPI groups by anomaly_count. For each selected group, scan the group's metric rows in the incident window and mark rows where value > p95 as anomaly. Identify consecutive anomaly runs where timestamps are consecutive minutes (difference exactly 60 seconds). For each run produce: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_ts (epoch), run_end_ts (epoch), length (number of points), max_value (max value in the run), p95, severity_ratio = (max_value - p95) / p95. Store the full runs table in kernel variable metric_fault_runs. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of these runs sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_ts, run_end_ts, length, max_value, p95, severity_ratio. If no runs of length >=2 exist, still return any single-point runs but mark length accordingly." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and metric-level anomaly detection: global P95 thresholds per component-KPI were computed from the full metric series, metric anomalies within the incident window (2021-03-07 11:00–11:30 CST) were identified and grouped into consecutive runs. The strongest metric signals are application-level (app.mrt) spikes for ServiceTest3/4/5 at 11:29–11:30, with ServiceTest5 showing the largest relative breach. These ServiceTest* components are not in the allowed root-cause component list. Among allowed components, small but present anomalies are: Redis02 (filesystem inode and redis CPU metrics, some at ~11:28), Tomcat02 (memory NoCacheMemPerc at ~11:01), MG01 (JVM thread/runtime small deviations), and apache01 (small CPU deviations). Trace analysis found many row_count anomalies across MG and dockerA/B groups and some duration increases; several trace row_count anomalies have earliest timestamps spanning the full window (11:00 and 11:29), and duration anomalies include MG01 trace.from_dockerA2.duration_mean around 11:04–11:10. Crucially, error_logs.csv contains error entries from apache02 at 2021-03-07 11:29:04 and 11:29:09 CST, which temporally coincide with the app.mrt spikes at 11:29. This co-occurrence suggests apache02 may be implicated. However, we need concrete evidence linking allowed components (apache02 or others) to the observed metric/trace faults. The next step is focused log evidence: retrieve all error log rows in the incident window (and counts per component) to see which allowed components produced errors and at what precise timestamps; this will help correlate metric/trace anomalies to a candidate root-cause component.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter error_logs.csv to timestamps >=1615086000 and <=1615087800. Return: (1) a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns timestamp (converted to UTC+8 readable), cmdb_id, and message (truncate message to 200 chars); (2) an aggregate count of error log rows per cmdb_id within the window (sorted by count desc). Keep outputs bounded and store the filtered error rows in a kernel variable named error_logs_window."}

Review summary: Metrics, traces, and logs consistently point to Tomcat03 at ~2021-03-07 11:29:00 CST. Traces show very high request durations to Tomcat03 from IG01/IG02 at 11:29; Tomcat03 metrics show connector thread exhaustion and a large TCP CLOSE-WAIT spike at 11:29–11:30; apache02 produced error logs at 11:29 shortly after. These signals indicate Tomcat03 experienced connection-handling failures likely caused by elevated network latency impacting request processing and causing thread buildup.

